<TITLE> Iran should halt sensitive atom work, Ebadi says </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TEHRAN, Nov 19 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Iranian Nobel Peace Prize laureate Shirin Ebadi called on the Islamic Republic on Monday to suspend sensitive nuclear activities, saying there was a `serious' threat of a US military attack. The West suspects Iran of developing nuclear weapons and speculation has grown that the United States may launch air strikes against it over its refusal to halt uranium enrichment. "Iran should respect UN Security Council resolutions and it means suspending uranium enrichment and resolving the dispute (on the nuclear issue) through talks," Ebadi, a leading human rights lawyer, told reporters. Iran says its nuclear programme is peaceful and has repeatedly refused to halt enrichment, a process to make fuel for power plants that can also provide material for bombs. Criticising the handling of Iran's nuclear policy is sensitive because it is considered a matter of national security. President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad has branded critics who want Iran to suspend uranium enrichment as "traitors". Ebadi, who was speaking at a conference of her rights group called "No to war, Yes to peace and human rights", called on all Iranians to support a national campaign aimed at preventing possible US military action. Ebadi, who won the Nobel Peace Prize in 2003, said the threat of conflict was "serious." "This campaign will pressure the (Iranian) establishment to prevent a war by accepting international commitments ... and respecting UN resolutions," she said. Iran's leading reformist parties and some senior clerics, including reformist former president Mohammad Khatami, have warned of an escalating crisis with the international community and called for a review of nuclear policy. Visiting Bahrain on Saturday, Ahmadinejad said Iran was ready to respond if attacked, but played down the prospect of war with the United Stat
